  <datafield tag="245" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Hydrogen and helium recycling from a JxB -force convected liquid metal Ga 67 In 20.5 Sn 12.5 under steady state plasma bombardment</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="260" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="c">2017-04</subfield>
    <subfield code="t">published</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="300" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">5</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">A series of first-of-a-kind laboratory-scale experiments on the JxB -force convected liquid metal divertor concept have been carried out in the temperature range from room temperature to ∼200 °C, employing a eutectic alloy: Ga 67 In 20.5 Sn 12.5 , the melting point of which is 10.5 °C. The electrical current conducted through the alloy is set at about 70A and the magnetic field is set at about 700 G. It has reproducibly been observed that hydrogen as well as helium particle recycling is noticeably reduced under steady state plasma bombardment when the liquid is convected by the JxB force.</subfield>
